 their separate lives and how the threat posed by cancer brought them a new, profound, and shared sense of meaning. Combining memoir, ethnography, and philosophy through a series of interconnected narratives, he tells a story of remarkable friendship and the quest for well-being. It’s a story of difference and unity, of illness and health, a lyrical reflection on human resiliency and the shoulders we lean on.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnthropologistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aInterracial friendshipvCase studies. 0aNigerienszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aSonghai (African people)zNigervBiography. 0aStoller, Paul.;Songhai (African people) -- Niger -- Biography.;Nigeriens -- New York (State) -- New York -- Biography.;Anthropologists -- United States -- Biography.;Interracial friendship -- Case studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aniger, immigrant, trader, africa, songhay, memoir, biography, ethnography, cancer, terminal illness, friendship, anthropology, ethnicity, language, culture, african market, harlem, art, commerce, business, community, belayara, silver spring, maryland, peace corps, new york, meaning, philosophy, resilience, health, race, nonfiction, immigration, warehouse, transnational.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226178967423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226178967/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles